fields.physical_description:
1.  SKYBIRDS INSTRUCTION CHART FOR ASSEMBLY, NO. 3A
HAWKER HURRICANE IIC.  Sheet printed on both side to show the title and trade mark of Givjoy, a history of the aircraft, assembly instructions and painting instructions.  At the bottom of the second side are details about joining the Skybird League and the address Skybirds, 9 Southampton Place, High Holborn, London, WC1.    (9½in x 5 3/4in)
2.  SKYBIRD DRG. NO. 3A HURRICANE IIC.  Sheet printed to show three line drawings of the aircraft from the top, side and front angles.  On the reverse side is a small pencil drawing of the cockpit cover.  (9½ x 6¼in)
3.  fuselage, darkish wood with the cockpit cut out and the area for the wings and tail wings shaped.  (L. 4½in)
4.  wingspan, light wood with cut out sections at the front and back centre to fit into the fuselage.  Additional cut out sections and small holes are shown to eventually take wheel struts and armaments.  (W.  6 5/8in)
5.  paper bag to house the extra parts; printed in black to show the title and contents.  (4¼in x 2½in)
6,7.  propeller, cast lead.  One blade has been broken off (7)
8,9.  undercarriage legs; thin plates of shaped steel, slightly rusted.
10-12.  wheel, metal.  (10,11) are the large front wheels and (12) the small rear tail wheel.   
13,14.  tail upright and wing which slot together and also into a slot at the end of the fuselage; compressed card in a red red colour.
15.  exhaust pipe, wood with diagonal cut away edge.  (L. 5/8in)
16,17.  two metal lengths; one is for the wireless mast
18,19.  metal pins for the undercarriage legs
20-23.  transfers sheet.  (20,21) show the RAF circles red, blue and white with a yellow band around the outside; (22) RAF circles of red and blue; (23) RAF stripes of red, white and blue.  (20-22) are printed on the back with instructions of how to soak the circles off the paper; each numbered 7/17.
24.  cockpit cover, transparent celluloid, trade name CELASTOID
*With the obvious pieces are several small pieces of wood, some cut into shapes.
25.  light wood shaped with a tongue cut away to one end.  It has been smoothed and rubbed with sandpaper.  (L. 3/4in)
26.  a similar piece in a rougher state; the tongue shape has only been partly formed
27.  small block of a similar pattern but with no tongue shape.
28,29.  two strips of light balsa wood
30.  length of wood, marked with a pencil line
31.  narrow length of dark wood
32.  rectangle of dark wood
33.  original packaging,  thick brown paper marked SKYBIRDS HURRICANE  in pen.  Between 1940 and 1945, card boxes were not available and the toys were carefully wrapped in sheet of brown paper folded as diamonds rather than squares.  This sheet is damaged.

*With this aircraft kit was a number of celluloid cockpit covers in their original paper bags and also a notice to customers
34.  SKYBIRDS TRANSPARENT COCKPIT COVERS 20/8/42
Owing to Government control of all Celastoid materials for War needs we regret being unable for the time being to supply transparent cockpit covers.
A suitable piece of wood is enclosed which modellers can cut to shape and paint to represent a Cabin.  It is possible many modellers will possess a small piece of transparent material from which they can create a cover.
printed in red.
*The following are brown paper bags sealed with tape and unopened.  They contain various celluloid shapes and each is stamped with the name of the aircraft.
35.  STIRLING
36.  MARAUDER
37.  FORTRESS
38.  a similar bag, named LANCASTER is badly torn and its contents missing, however, some of  the following pieces are probably from this bag.
*Various shapes of transparent celluloid castings; soem appear to have been cut.
39.  cockpit cover, long and narow
40.  cockpit cover, short and broad
41.  nose cone shape, crimped along top edge; no underside
42.  nose cone shape, with underside and top crimped
43.  round bulbous shape crimped around the bottom edge
44.  round bulbous shape moulded in a square sheet of celluloid
45.  large bottle shape hand cut around the bottom edge
fields.title: SKYBIRD HURRICANE
fields.marks: GIVJOY within the shape of a stylized bird `REGISTERED TRADE MARK' below
fields.history_note:
References: As a result of restrictions during the 2nd World War, British toy makers had to use any materials which were both available and permitted by the government.  These models predate the more famous Airfix kits but are of the same 1:72 scale

Alfred James Holladay (A J Holladay & Co Ltd), 32,33 Aldermanbury Road, London.  GIVJOY was registered as a trademark in 1920 but it had been in use from 1916.
fields.production_note: Made by: A J Holladay & Co. Ltd, London (Alfred James).
